VISUAL & PROGRAMMATIC ASSESSMENT¶

Visual Assessment already done with MS Excel and Google Sheet and columns of interest were easily identified

First round of Programmatic Assessment would be done on a general basis for all the columns and rows in the dataset

Second round of Programmatic Assessment will be done on a copy of the dataset to which the identified columns of interest have been assigned and this would feature column-specific inspection.

Link to Dataset and Loan Dictionary: https://bit.ly/prosper-loan-dataset

converting to categorical dtype¶

# importing CategoricalDtype
from pandas.api.types import CategoricalDtype
In [62]:
# due to the need to specify order in our Categorical variables as our project warrants
# we create a dictionary to specify the order we want our categorical variables to follow
conversion_dict = {
    'Term': [12, 36, 60],
    'LoanStatus': ['Cancelled', 'Chargedoff', 'Completed', 'Current',
                  'Defaulted', 'FinalPaymentInProgress',
                  'Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Past Due (16-30 days)',
                  'Past Due (31-60 days)', 'Past Due (61-90 days)',
                  'Past Due (91-120 days)', 'Past Due (>120 days)'],
    'IncomeRange': ['$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999',
                  '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+', 'Not displayed',
                  'Not employed'],
    'EmploymentStatus': ['Employed', 'Full-time', 'Not available', 'Not employed',
                  'Other', 'Part-time', 'Retired', 'Self-employed']
}

# here, we set the order we have created 
for category in conversion_dict:
    set_order = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(categories=conversion_dict[category], ordered=True)
    loan_data[category] = loan_data[category].astype(set_order)

def reg_plot(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating reg plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    ax = sns.regplot(x=x, y=y, color='b')

# Plot_bar function to help with plotting bars using Seaborn
def bar_plot(x, y, height, labels = None, title = None, 
             xlabel = None, ylabel=None, color = None):
    sns.set_style('darkgrid')
    plt.bar(x, y, height, tick_label = labels, color = color, width = 0.2)
    plt.title(title, weight = 'bold', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, weight = 'bold', fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, weight = 'bold', fontsize = 12)
    plt.show
In [68]:
def count_plot(data=None, x=None, y=None, hue=None, color=None, height=None, width=None, 
               title=None, order=None, xlabel=None, ylabel=None, rotation=None, **kwargs):
    
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(width,height)})
    
    sns.countplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, hue=hue, color=color, order=order, **kwargs)
    plt.title(title, weight = 'bold', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation);
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, weight = 'medium', fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, weight = 'medium', fontsize = 12)
    plt.show
In [69]:
def factor_plot(x, y, data=None, xlabel=None, ylabel=None, 
                title=None, rotation=None, height=None, width=None, **kwargs):
    
    plt.figure(figsize=[height,width])
        
    # Function to add a main title to all subplots
    plt.suptitle(title.title(), y = 1,
            fontsize = 15, weight = "bold")
    
    # Function to maximize distance between subplots
    plt.tight_layout()
    
    # Function to create violin plot
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    sns.violinplot(data=data, x=x,y=y)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation);
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, weight = 'medium', fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, weight = 'medium', fontsize = 12)
    plt.show

    # Function to create box plot
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=x,y=y)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation);
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, weight = 'medium', fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, weight = 'medium', fontsize = 12)
    plt.show

PERCENTAGE (%) OF ORIGINAL DATA RETAINED¶

In [76]:
Retainance_Perc = (float(loan_non_null_df.shape[0]/loan_data.shape[0])*100) 
Retainance_Perc
Out[76]:
90.61586666315596
Note:¶

It wouldn't be a bad idea to drop all NaN entries/null values as there is still a large percentage of the dataset retained however, due to the uneven distribution of null values, I wouldn't do this straightaway.

The NaN/null values per column when inspected visually doesn't happen to fall in the same row across all the columns, meaning someone could be missing an IncomeRange entry but have their BorrowerState entry filled. Therefore dropping the null values across the dataframe so quickly would eliminate the chance of counting such person's BorrowerState during a CountPlot

That said, the Exploratory Data Analysis from here on shall be done as follows:

(1) For univariate plots and QVOs (Question-Visualization-Observation) requiring just one column to answer, we would drop the NaNs per column while attempting to answer and plot them.

(2) For those QVOs requiring a combination of two columns or more, we would use the cleaner non-null dataframe like the loan_non_null_df (with over 90% Data Retainance Percentage) to answer and plot them.

Out[134]:
Text(0.5, 1, 'A Plot Loan Status Per Employment Status Per Loan Term')

When partitioned by Loan Status, it is quickly observed that mostly Employed people have active loans they are servicing and they are the only ones who have loans that are past due. Self employed people don't have active loans as compared to employed ones and as one would rightly assume they are the only set of applicants who are likely to get a loan since there's need for a refund. As dor the loan refund, only those with full time employment have their numbers up and that isn't necessarily becuase of how good they are, it could be because they are the ones who apply the most.

Current loans are being served in most of the salary ranges. For the 36 months loans, the loans peak at the 50,000k-74,999k USD range before a slight variation in the heavy earners category. For the longer loan schemes of 60 months, the peak is also at the 50,000k-74,999k USD range and it is an increase from the previous income ranges but they have fewer people who are in process of making their final payment. The active loan count pretty much stays the same for the heavy earners and same thing applies for those who are in process of making their final payment.
